ms' entry into the mainstream. Instead the book suggests that the dynamics and trajectory of 'dissident' republicanism are shaped more by contemporary forces than historical tradition and that by understanding the "dissidents" we can better understand the emerging forms of political challenge in an age of austerity and increasing political instability internationally.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aRepublicanismzIrelandxHistoryy20th century. 0aRepublicanismzIrelandxHistoryy21st century. 4aPolitical Studies 2019. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Ideologies / General.2bisacsh  aContinuity IRA.  aGood Friday Agreement.  aIRA ceasefires.  aIRA decommissioning.  aIrish republicanism.  aMaghaberry prison.  aNorthern Ireland policing.  aProvisional Movement.  aSinn Féin.  a‘Dissident’ republicans.1 aMcGlinchey, Marisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152611621540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526116215423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526116215/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles